<?xml-stylesheet type="text/xsl" href="assets/xml/rss.xsl" media="all"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Colour Science</title><link>https://www.colour-science.org/</link><description>Colour: Colour Science for Python</description><atom:link href="https://www.colour-science.org/rss.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><language>en</language><copyright>Contents © 2022 &lt;a href="mailto:colour-developers@colour-science.org"&gt;Colour Developers&lt;/a&gt; </copyright><lastBuildDate>Sun, 30 Jan 2022 07:25:43 GMT</lastBuildDate><generator>Nikola (getnikola.com)</generator><docs>http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/tech/rss</docs><item><title>The ColorChecker Considered Mostly Harmless</title><link>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/the-colorchecker-considered-mostly-harmless/</link><dc:creator>Colour Developers</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;This post will be about colour rendition charts, e.g.
&lt;em&gt;X-Rite ColorChecker Classic&lt;/em&gt;, their usage and its dangers. It was a long time
coming and some discussions accelerated the authoring. If you are in a hurry
and do not want to read the entire post, the &lt;em&gt;TLDR&lt;/em&gt; is as follows:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="alert alert-dismissible alert-warning"&gt;&lt;em&gt;Unless you have all the relevant spectral measurements&lt;/em&gt;, a colour
rendition chart should not be used to perform colour-correction of camera
imagery but only for white balancing and relative exposure adjustments.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There is granularity in everything, and we will present, in the conclusion,
some contexts when performing colour-correction is a good idea.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.colour-science.org/posts/the-colorchecker-considered-mostly-harmless/"&gt;Read more…&lt;/a&gt; (6 min remaining to read)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><category>camera</category><category>colour rendition chart</category><category>colour science</category><guid>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/the-colorchecker-considered-mostly-harmless/</guid><pubDate>Sat, 06 Mar 2021 01:16:33 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Colour 0.3.16 is available!</title><link>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/colour-0316-is-available/</link><dc:creator>Colour Developers</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://github.com/colour-science/colour/releases/tag/v0.3.16"&gt;Colour 0.3.16&lt;/a&gt;
has finally been released!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.colour-science.org/posts/colour-0316-is-available/"&gt;Read more…&lt;/a&gt; (2 min remaining to read)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><category>colour</category><category>colour science</category><category>release</category><guid>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/colour-0316-is-available/</guid><pubDate>Fri, 27 Nov 2020 23:24:16 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Our First 1000 Stars on Github!</title><link>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/our-first-1000-stars-on-github/</link><dc:creator>Colour Developers</dc:creator><description>&lt;p&gt;h   t   m   l   &amp;gt;   &lt;/p&gt;</description><category>colour</category><category>colour science</category><category>github</category><guid>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/our-first-1000-stars-on-github/</guid><pubDate>Mon, 28 Sep 2020 08:39:40 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Physical Lighting Quantities: Tying Both Ends</title><link>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/physical-lighting-quantities-tying-both-ends/</link><dc:creator>Colour Developers</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Validation against ground truth data is an important step when implementing
support for physical lighting quantities in a realtime or offline renderer.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In this post, a simple but effective method to assess that the physical camera
model behaves as expected against ground truth data (or conversely) will be
presented.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.colour-science.org/posts/physical-lighting-quantities-tying-both-ends/"&gt;Read more…&lt;/a&gt; (6 min remaining to read)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><category>absolute luminance calibration</category><category>colour science</category><category>digital still camera exposure model</category><category>physical quantities</category><guid>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/physical-lighting-quantities-tying-both-ends/</guid><pubDate>Wed, 01 Apr 2020 07:28:05 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Colour 0.3.15 is available!</title><link>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/colour-0315-is-available/</link><dc:creator>Colour Developers</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://github.com/colour-science/colour/releases/tag/v0.3.15"&gt;Colour 0.3.15&lt;/a&gt;
is available!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.colour-science.org/posts/colour-0315-is-available/"&gt;Read more…&lt;/a&gt; (1 min remaining to read)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><category>colour</category><category>colour science</category><category>release</category><guid>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/colour-0315-is-available/</guid><pubDate>Sat, 25 Jan 2020 08:44:09 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>PyCharm, Vagrant, Ansible &amp; Poetry</title><link>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/pycharm-vagrant-ansible-poetry/</link><dc:creator>Colour Developers</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;div class="alert alert-dismissible alert-info line-block"&gt;
&lt;div class="line"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Note&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="line"&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="line"&gt;This post is an update to the
&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://www.colour-science.org/posts/pycharm-vagrant-fabric-anaconda/"&gt;PyCharm, Vagrant, Fabric &amp;amp; Anaconda&lt;/a&gt; post.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Installing the whole development toolchain for &lt;strong&gt;Colour&lt;/strong&gt; roughly means
deploying:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul class="simple"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://www.python.org/download/releases/"&gt;python&amp;gt;=3.6&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="http://imageio.github.io/"&gt;imageio&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pypi.org/project/scipy/"&gt;scipy&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pypi.org/project/six/"&gt;six&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pypi.org/project/networkx/"&gt;networkx&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://github.com/OpenImageIO/oiio"&gt;openimageio&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pypi.org/project/pandas/"&gt;pandas&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pypi.org/project/matplotlib/"&gt;matplotlib&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://www.graphviz.org/"&gt;graphviz&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pypi.org/project/pygraphviz/"&gt;pygraphviz&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pypi.org/project/backports.functools-lru-cache/"&gt;backports.functools_lru_cache&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pypi.org/project/biblib-simple/"&gt;biblib-simple&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pypi.org/project/coverage/"&gt;coverage&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pypi.org/project/coveralls/"&gt;coveralls&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pypi.org/project/flake8/"&gt;flake8&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pypi.org/project/invoke/"&gt;invoke&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pypi.org/project/jupyter/"&gt;jupyter&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pypi.org/project/mock/"&gt;mock&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pypi.org/project/nbformat/"&gt;nbformat&amp;gt;=4&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pypi.org/project/nose/"&gt;nose&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pypi.org/project/pre-commit/"&gt;pre-commit&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pypi.org/project/pytest/"&gt;pytest&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pypi.org/project/restructuredtext-lint/"&gt;restructuredtext-lint&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pypi.org/project/Sphinx/"&gt;sphinx&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pypi.org/project/sphinx-rtd-theme/"&gt;sphinx-rtd-theme&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pypi.org/project/sphinxcontrib-bibtex/"&gt;sphinxcontrib-bibtex&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pypi.org/project/twine/"&gt;twine&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://pypi.org/project/yapf/"&gt;yapf==0.23.0&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;... and too many things I just don't remember!&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I decided to see how I could make that setup a bit more portable and easier to
deploy.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;That's where &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://www.vagrantup.com/"&gt;Vagrant&lt;/a&gt; kicks in along
&lt;a class="reference external" href="http://www.jetbrains.com/pycharm/"&gt;PyCharm&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://www.ansible.com/"&gt;Ansible&lt;/a&gt;
and &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://poetry.eustace.io"&gt;Poetry&lt;/a&gt;!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The following guide assume that you have that you have &lt;em&gt;PyCharm&lt;/em&gt; installed and
are using &lt;em&gt;macOS&lt;/em&gt;, although it should pretty much be platform agnostic.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.colour-science.org/posts/pycharm-vagrant-ansible-poetry/"&gt;Read more…&lt;/a&gt; (5 min remaining to read)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><category>ansible</category><category>poetry</category><category>pycharm</category><category>vagrant</category><guid>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/pycharm-vagrant-ansible-poetry/</guid><pubDate>Sat, 09 Nov 2019 02:46:40 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>NumFOCUS, Colour 0.3.14 and Colour - Datasets 0.1.0!</title><link>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/numfocus-colour-0314-and-colour-datasets-010/</link><dc:creator>Colour Developers</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;We are delighted to announce that &lt;strong&gt;Colour&lt;/strong&gt; has joined the
&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://numfocus.org/"&gt;NumFOCUS&lt;/a&gt;  affiliated projects and that
&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://github.com/colour-science/colour/releases/tag/v0.3.14"&gt;Colour 0.3.14&lt;/a&gt;
has been released over the weekend along with
&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://github.com/colour-science/colour-datasets/releases/tag/v0.1.0"&gt;Colour - Datasets 0.1.0&lt;/a&gt;,
a new &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://www.python.org/"&gt;Python&lt;/a&gt; package dedicated to colour science
datasets management.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.colour-science.org/posts/numfocus-colour-0314-and-colour-datasets-010/"&gt;Read more…&lt;/a&gt; (4 min remaining to read)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><guid>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/numfocus-colour-0314-and-colour-datasets-010/</guid><pubDate>Sun, 27 Oct 2019 08:39:18 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>sRGB EOTF: Pure Gamma 2.2 Function or Piece-Wise Function?</title><link>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/srgb-eotf-pure-gamma-22-or-piece-wise-function/</link><dc:creator>Colour Developers</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;A topic that caused a great deal of
&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://www.liftgammagain.com/forum/index.php?threads/dealing-with-srgb.13239/"&gt;passionate&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://twitter.com/troy_s/status/1170094480080265217"&gt;discussions&lt;/a&gt; is that
of the &lt;em&gt;sRGB&lt;/em&gt; &lt;strong&gt;Electro-Optical Transfer Function&lt;/strong&gt; (&lt;strong&gt;EOTF&lt;/strong&gt;): Should it be
the &lt;em&gt;pure Gamma 2.2 function&lt;/em&gt; or the &lt;em&gt;piece-wise function&lt;/em&gt; defined in
&lt;em&gt;IEC 61966-2-1:1999 Standard&lt;/em&gt;?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.colour-science.org/posts/srgb-eotf-pure-gamma-22-or-piece-wise-function/"&gt;Read more…&lt;/a&gt; (4 min remaining to read)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><category>colour</category><category>colour science</category><category>EOTF</category><category>sRGB</category><category>transfer function</category><guid>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/srgb-eotf-pure-gamma-22-or-piece-wise-function/</guid><pubDate>Fri, 25 Oct 2019 19:54:39 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Colour 0.3.13 is available!</title><link>https://www.colour-science.org/posts/colour-0313-is-available/</link><dc:creator>Colour Developers</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://github.com/colour-science/colour/releases/tag/v0.3.13"&gt;Colour 0.3.13&lt;/a&gt;
